{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:09:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:09:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15641"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8332"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8332"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"10106"},{"type":"tags","id":"10111"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20103"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents with an eight-month history of weight gain, particularly around her trunk and face. She has developed purple striae on her abdomen, easy bruising, and proximal muscle weakness. Laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMorning cortisol: 850 nmol/L (140-690)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EACTH: 95 ng/L (10-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following receptors would be most activated in this clinical scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MC1 receptors","MC2 receptors","MC3 receptors","MC4 receptors","MC5 receptors"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with Cushing syndrome, likely due to an ACTH-secreting pituitary adenoma (Cushing disease). The elevated ACTH would primarily activate \u003Cstrong\u003EMC2 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E on adrenocortical cells, leading to increased cortisol production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other melanocortin receptors have different functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMC1 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are found in melanocytes and regulate skin pigmentation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMC3 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in energy homeostasis in the brain and peripheral tissues\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMC4 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E regulate appetite and metabolism in the central nervous system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMC5 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E are found in exocrine glands and other peripheral tissues\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high ACTH levels continuously stimulate MC2 receptors, resulting in excess cortisol production and the characteristic clinical features of Cushing syndrome including central obesity, striae, easy bruising, and proximal myopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) binds specifically to melanocortin-2 (MC2) receptors on adrenocortical cells to stimulate cortisol production.","Elevated ACTH and cortisol levels with characteristic clinical features suggest Cushing disease.","The most common cause of endogenous Cushing syndrome is ACTH-secreting pituitary adenoma."],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA.","Allen MJ, Sharma S. Physiology, Adrenocorticotropic Hormone (ACTH) [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500031/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56494"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56494"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T18:59:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T19:00:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8332"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74",